"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.935em;\"><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-3.2em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.2em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\" style=\"padding-left:1em;\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.895em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.2em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"min-width:1.02em;height:1.28em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width='400em' height='1.28em' viewBox='0 0 400000 1296' preserveAspectRatio='xMinYMin slice'><path d='M263,681c0.7,0,18,39.7,52,119\nc34,79.3,68.167,158.7,102.5,238c34.3,79.3,51.8,119.3,52.5,120\nc340,-704.7,510.7,-1060.3,512,-1067\nl0 -0\nc4.7,-7.3,11,-11,19,-11\nH40000v40H1012.3\ns-271.3,567,-271.3,567c-38.7,80.7,-84,175,-136,283c-52,108,-89.167,185.3,-111.5,232\nc-22.3,46.7,-33.8,70.3,-34.5,71c-4.7,4.7,-12.3,7,-23,7s-12,-1,-12,-1\ns-109,-253,-109,-253c-72.7,-168,-109.3,-252,-110,-252c-10.7,8,-22,16.7,-34,26\nc-22,17.3,-33.3,26,-34,26s-26,-26,-26,-26s76,-59,76,-59s76,-60,76,-60z\nM1001 80h400000v40h-400000z'/></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.305em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"Ar9neAv5NP"}],"key":"DZiKpSAITK"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"Zb98NauigN"}],"key":"tf3FIQBXZv"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"Suppose a student answers 20 true/false questions completely at random. Use a normal approximation to estimate the probability of getting no more than 8 correct. The number (X) correct is a binomial random variable that represents the number of successes in 20 trials when the probability of success for each trial is .5. X has a mean and standard deviation of:\n\n$\\mu=np=20(0.5)=10,\\sigma=\\sqrt{np(1-p)}=\\sqrt{20(0.5)(1-0.5)}=2.24$\n\nand so we approximate the binomial X with a normal random variable having the same mean and standard deviation:\n\n```{figure} images/image182.gif\n:alt: A probability histogram with a probability distribution curve drawn on top. The vertical axis is labeled \"Probability\" and the horizontal axis is labeled \"X.\" The histogram is for binomial X, with mean=10 and standard deviation of 2.24 . The normal curve is for normal X, with mean 10 and standard deviation of 2.24 , the same as for the histogram.\n\nA probability histogram with a probability distribution curve drawn on top. The vertical axis is labeled \"Probability\" and the horizontal axis is labeled \"X.\" The histogram is for binomial X, with mean=10 and standard deviation of 2.24 . The normal curve is for normal X, with mean 10 and standard deviation of 2.24 , the same as for the histogram.\n```\n\nThen we solve in the usual way using normal tables:\n\n$P(X_{B}\\leq8)\\approxP(X_{N}\\leq8)=P(Z\\leq\\frac{8-10}{2.24})=P(Z\\leq-0.89)=0.1867$","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"key":"xhT6oxICcE"}],"key":"kja8tGJLwx"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Unfortunately, the approximated probability, .1867, is quite a bit different from the actual probability, .2517. However, this example constitutes something of a “worst-case scenario” according to the usual criteria for use of a normal approximation.","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"vxcmXVBSez"}],"key":"u5oQqPpYUq"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Rule of Thumb","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"a6mtqo2faT"}],"identifier":"rule-of-thumb","label":"Rule of Thumb","html_id":"rule-of-thumb","implicit":true,"key":"esv1KwZBjV"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Probabilities for a binomial random variable X with n and p may be approximated by those for a normal random variable having the same mean and standard deviation as long as the sample size n is large enough relative to the proportions of successes and failures, p and 1 - p. Our Rule of Thumb will be to require that","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"key":"k8cyBTLzVg"}],"key":"TBi46aPCsy"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"inlineMath","value":"np\\geq10","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>p</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">np\\geq10</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8304em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≥</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">10</span></span></span></span>","key":"UTZWB1iJtq"},{"type":"text","value":" and ","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":